            <lb n="4"/>
               diae
               <persName>
                  <name type="geniticulum" key="Valeria"><unclear>V</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ale</supplied></name>
               </persName>
            <lb n="5"/>
               <persName>
                  <name type="geniticulum" key="Valeria">riae</name>
               </persName>
            <lb n="6"/>
               sua<supplied reason="lost">e</supplied>
               <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown"/>
            <lb n="7"/>
               <expan><abbr>b</abbr><ex>ene</ex></expan>
               <supplied reason="lost">
                  <expan><abbr>m</abbr><ex>erenti</ex></expan>
                  <expan><abbr>f</abbr><ex>ecit</ex></expan>.
               </supplied>          
         </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>
               To the divine spirits. Marcus Valerius Sosimus....made (this) for well-deserving Valeria, his [...].
            </p>
         </div>
         <div type="apparatus">
            <p>
               Lines 4-5: CIL supplies Veneria as the addressee of this epitaph, while Olcott supplies Valeria. Given
               that there is already a Valerius in this epitaph, Olcott's interpretation seems slightly more plausible
               and is taken here.
            </p>
            <p>
              Line 6: Similarly, CIL supplies "coniugi" where Olcott supplies nothing. Since there is ambiguity whether
              Valeria is a wife or a daughter, nothing is supplied here.
            </p>
         </div>
